<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE NATION; NEBRASKA'S FRAZIER HAS BLOOD 
CLOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tommie Frazier, quarterback for No. 2 Nebraska and a strong contender for the 
Heisman Trophy, might be sidelined for the rest of the season because of a 
blood clot in his right calf. 
</P>
<P>
 Coach Tom Osborne said Frazier was admitted Sunday to Bryan Hospital in 
Lincoln.Frazier, a junior and key to Nebraska's option offense, will sit out 
Saturday's game against Wyoming, Osborne said. Brook Berringer has been 
Frazier's backup. 
</P>
<P>
 "It could be a few weeks, it could be the season. At this point nobody knows," 
Osborne said. 
</P>
<P>
 Team doctor Pat Clare said the blood clot was being treated with enzymes and 
blood thinner. The clot has shrunk 25 percent since treatment began Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's responding very well," Clare said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
