<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Mark Platte, S, STON, ; Rene Lynch 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 OH DANNY BOY: Sometimes prosecutors' compliments come from the people they 
send to prison. Mission Viejo socialite Danny Hernandez, now serving a six-year 
sentence in a multimillion-dollar fraud scheme, wants a new attorney to handle 
an appeal for him. . . . Hernandez complains that he got a raw deal in the plea 
agreement his lawyers worked out with Assistant U.S. Atty. Steve Wolfe. 
Hernandez has written from prison that his lawyers let Wolfe "bully" them: "I 
feel I was left out in the cold as far as my plea agreement." 
</P>
<P>
 CAN'T DUCK THIS SHOT: The Visiting Nurse Assn. of Orange County, a nonprofit 
home health group, is trying to spread the word that it's flu season again. So 
it's kicking off its annual flu shot campaign by lining up some mighty 
high-profile people to immunize today: the players and coaches of The Mighty 
Ducks. . . . You can find a flu clinic in your neighborhood by calling (800) 
616-SHOT. 
</P>
<P>
 FAST THROWER: How would you like a pitcher with these stats: 145 strikeouts in 
60 innings -- then he hits .687 when it's his turn to bat. Those are the Little 
League numbers for 12-year-old Jared Fast of Huntington Beach, 5-8, 210 pounds. 
. . . He took first place for his age group last weekend in Dallas at the Major 
League Baseball's pitch, hit and run finals for youngsters. Fast's reward: a 
trip for two to next year's All-Star game in Texas -- if the baseball strike is 
settled. 
</P>
<P>
 NO JOKE HERE: If you're tired of bad lawyer jokes, here's a brighter look at 
the local bar. The Orange County Bar Assn. has just been awarded the 
prestigious Pro Bono Service award for public service by the California Bar for 
its efforts to assist victims of last year's Laguna Beach fires. . . . The 
bar's fire relief task force trained more than 100 attorneys in the basics of 
disaster legal services. Those attorneys then gave free legal advice through 
the Disaster Application Center in Laguna Beach. 
</P>
