<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: WOODLAND HILLS; SBA OPENS A NEW OFFICE FOR QUAKE AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIO MORAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Small Business Administration opened a new facility Monday in Woodland 
Hills to provide a more convenient location to process loan applications for 
victims of the Northridge earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 The center is in suites 504 through 506 in the Fallbrook Mall, 6633 Fallbrook 
Ave.Earthquake victims who have already received SBA loan applications can get 
individual help in filling out the forms or sign closing loan papers at the new 
center, according to SBA spokesman Rick Jenkins. 
</P>
<P>
 The facility is the third such center operated by the SBA. The other two are 
in Koreatown near Downtown Los Angeles and in Northridge. The Northridge center 
is at 17030 Devonshire St. All three are open Mondays through Fridays from 9 
a.m to 6 p.m. and Saturdays 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The SBA also offers its services at Earthquake Service Centers, run jointly by 
the Federal Emergency Management Agency and the California Office of Emergency 
Services, in Chatsworth, Fillmore, Simi Valley, Valencia, the Crenshaw 
district, Hollywood, Sherman Oaks, Sylmar and Van Nuys. 
</P>
<P>
 The deadline for registering for assistance is Oct. 17. JULIO MORAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
