<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: HEALTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Doctors Mull Forming HMO: The California Medical Assn., a professional group 
representing 37,000 doctors, is in talks with Wausau Insurance Cos., of Wausau, 
Wisc., about forming a statewide physician-run health maintenance organization. 
CMA spokesman Paul Moreno said there is widespread dissatisfaction among 
doctors about the growing influence that for-profit HMOs and other managed care 
companies are having on their professional lives.The plan, to be called 
California Health Care, would include a statewide network of physicians that 
would seek contracts with large regional and statewide employers. The 
organization "will be philosophically dedicated to maximizing the percentage of 
(insurance premium dollars) spent on the delivery of health care and minimizing 
the percentage spent on administration and overhead," said Dr. Ronald P. 
Bangasser, president of the group. The CMA and Wausau hope to decide within 60 
days whether to go forward with the project, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
